    <p class="sl">Why it matters</p>
    <h2>Why Annual Wood Heater Servicing Is Essential</h2>
    <p>Every fire leaves behind creosote — a tar-like residue that coats the inside of your flue pipe. Over a season of regular use, that buildup restricts airflow, reduces the efficiency of your heater, and creates a genuine fire risk. Creosote is highly flammable. A chimney fire caused by creosote ignition burns at temperatures that can damage the flue lining and spread to the structure of your home.</p>
    <p>Beyond fire risk, a dirty flue is the most common cause of smoke coming back into the room, poor draw, fires that won't stay alight, and a persistent burning smell in the house when the heater isn't running.</p>
    <p>Annual servicing removes the buildup before it reaches dangerous levels, keeps the heater running efficiently, and is a requirement under most home insurance policies for wood heater coverage to be valid.</p>

    <div class="reason-grid" style="margin-top:1.5rem;">
      <div class="rc"><span class="rc-icon">&#128293;</span><div class="rc-title">Fire safety</div><div class="rc-desc">Creosote is the primary cause of chimney fires. Regular cleaning keeps it at safe levels.</div></div>
      <div class="rc"><span class="rc-icon">&#128168;</span><div class="rc-title">Better performance</div><div class="rc-desc">A clean flue draws properly — fires light faster and burn more efficiently.</div></div>
      <div class="rc"><span class="rc-icon">&#128203;</span><div class="rc-title">Insurance compliance</div><div class="rc-desc">Most policies require annual servicing for fire-related claims to be valid.</div></div>
      <div class="rc"><span class="rc-icon">&#128172;</span><div class="rc-title">Condition report</div><div class="rc-desc">You get a straight verbal report on the state of the flue and heater — no upselling, just facts.</div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <p class="sl">When to book</p>
    <h2>When Should You Get Your Wood Heater Serviced?</h2>
    <p>The best time is autumn — April through May — before the heating season starts. This means your heater is clean, inspected and ready to go when the cold arrives in late May. You also beat the winter rush, when booking availability tightens up significantly.</p>
    <p>If you've missed the autumn window and the heater is already running, you can still book mid-season — but don't leave it until the end of winter when buildup is at its worst and risk is highest.</p>
    <p>If the heater hasn't been serviced in more than a year, or you've moved into a home with an unknown service history, book before the next time you use it.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- POWER SWEEPING VS MANUAL COMPARISON -->
  <section class="sec" id="power-sweeping">
    <p class="sl">Why it matters</p>
    <h2>Power Sweeping vs Manual Brushes</h2>
    <p>Most chimney companies still use the same manual rod-and-brush method that's been around for decades. Dave uses professional rotary power sweeping equipment — an electric drill-powered rotary head that spins the brush at high speed, the same gear used by commercial operators. Here's the difference:</p>

    <!-- Visual comparison diagram -->
    <div class="sweep-visual">
      <div class="sweep-col sweep-col--power">
        <div class="sweep-col-header sweep-col-header--power">
          <span class="sweep-badge sweep-badge--power">✓ Power Sweeping</span>
          <span class="sweep-sub">Electric drill-powered — what Dave uses</span>
        </div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 160 220" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="sweep-svg" aria-label="Power sweeping equipment diagram">
          <!-- Chimney outline -->
          <rect x="55" y="10" width="50" height="150" rx="4" fill="#2d1a0e" opacity="0.12"/>
          <!-- Flue walls -->
          <rect x="60" y="14" width="40" height="142" rx="2" fill="#1a0a04" opacity="0.18"/>
          <!-- Motor unit at top -->
          <rect x="48" y="2" width="64" height="20" rx="5" fill="#c0392b"/>
          <text x="80" y="15" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#fff" font-family="sans-serif" font-weight="700">ELECTRIC DRILL</text>
          <!-- Spinning head — rotary brush -->
          <circle cx="80" cy="38" r="14" fill="none" stroke="#e87a3a" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-dasharray="4 2"/>
          <circle cx="80" cy="38" r="3" fill="#e87a3a"/>
          <!-- Rotary bristles radiating out -->
          <line x1="80" y1="24" x2="80" y2="18" stroke="#e87a3a" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="80" y1="52" x2="80" y2="58" stroke="#e87a3a" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="66" y1="38" x2="60" y2="38" stroke="#e87a3a" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="94" y1="38" x2="100" y2="38" stroke="#e87a3a" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="70" y1="28" x2="65" y2="23" stroke="#e87a3a" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="90" y1="28" x2="95" y2="23" stroke="#e87a3a" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="70" y1="48" x2="65" y2="53" stroke="#e87a3a" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="90" y1="48" x2="95" y2="53" stroke="#e87a3a" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <!-- Rotation arrows -->
          <path d="M 68 27 A 14 14 0 0 1 93 27" fill="none" stroke="#e87a3a" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.6"/>
          <polygon points="93,27 96,22 98,28" fill="#e87a3a" opacity="0.6"/>
          <!-- Flexible rod -->
          <rect x="78" y="52" width="4" height="80" rx="2" fill="#555"/>
          <!-- Soot particles being dislodged -->
          <circle cx="62" cy="45" r="2" fill="#333" opacity="0.5"/>
          <circle cx="100" cy="50" r="1.5" fill="#333" opacity="0.4"/>
          <circle cx="65" cy="60" r="1" fill="#333" opacity="0.35"/>
          <circle cx="97" cy="65" r="2" fill="#333" opacity="0.4"/>
          <circle cx="63" cy="75" r="1.5" fill="#333" opacity="0.3"/>
          <!-- HEPA vacuum connection indicator -->
          <rect x="88" y="155" width="34" height="12" rx="3" fill="#2c7a4b"/>
          <text x="105" y="164" text-anchor="middle" font-size="5.5" fill="#fff" font-family="sans-serif" font-weight="700">HEPA VAC</text>
          <line x1="80" y1="132" x2="88" y2="161" stroke="#2c7a4b" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="3 2"/>
          <!-- Labels -->
          <text x="80" y="185" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#333" font-family="sans-serif">Rotary head dislodges</text>
          <text x="80" y="195" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#333" font-family="sans-serif">all built-up creosote</text>
          <text x="80" y="210" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#2c7a4b" font-family="sans-serif" font-weight="700">Captured by HEPA vac</text>
        </svg>
        <ul class="sweep-points">
          <li><strong>Electric drill spins the brush</strong> at high RPM — scrubs all sides simultaneously</li>
          <li><strong>Removes hardened creosote</strong> — not just loose soot</li>
          <li><strong>HEPA-filtered vacuum</strong> captures particles before they enter the room</li>
          <li><strong>Takes 45–90 min</strong> for a thorough result</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="sweep-divider">VS</div>

      <div class="sweep-col sweep-col--manual">
        <div class="sweep-col-header sweep-col-header--manual">
          <span class="sweep-badge sweep-badge--manual">✗ Manual Brushes</span>
          <span class="sweep-sub">The old way</span>
        </div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 160 220" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="sweep-svg" aria-label="Manual brush diagram">
          <!-- Chimney outline -->
          <rect x="55" y="10" width="50" height="150" rx="4" fill="#2d1a0e" opacity="0.12"/>
          <!-- Flue walls -->
          <rect x="60" y="14" width="40" height="142" rx="2" fill="#1a0a04" opacity="0.18"/>
          <!-- Stiff rod -->
          <rect x="78" y="14" width="4" height="100" rx="2" fill="#888"/>
          <!-- Round brush head — smaller than flue -->
          <ellipse cx="80" cy="120" rx="10" ry="10" fill="none" stroke="#888" stroke-width="2"/>
          <line x1="72" y1="112" x2="70" y2="108" stroke="#888" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="88" y1="112" x2="90" y2="108" stroke="#888" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="72" y1="128" x2="70" y2="132" stroke="#888" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="88" y1="128" x2="90" y2="132" stroke="#888" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <!-- Gap indicators showing brush doesn't reach walls -->
          <line x1="60" y1="115" x2="70" y2="115" stroke="#c0392b" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="2 1"/>
          <line x1="90" y1="115" x2="100" y2="115" stroke="#c0392b" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="2 1"/>
          <text x="55" y="113" text-anchor="end" font-size="5" fill="#c0392b" font-family="sans-serif">gap</text>
          <text x="105" y="113" text-anchor="start" font-size="5" fill="#c0392b" font-family="sans-serif">gap</text>
          <!-- Creosote buildup on walls -->
          <rect x="60" y="30" width="5" height="110" fill="#1a0a04" opacity="0.4"/>
          <rect x="95" y="30" width="5" height="110" fill="#1a0a04" opacity="0.4"/>
          <!-- No vacuum — soot falls down -->
          <circle cx="68" cy="145" r="2" fill="#333" opacity="0.6"/>
          <circle cx="80" cy="148" r="2.5" fill="#333" opacity="0.55"/>
          <circle cx="92" cy="145" r="2" fill="#333" opacity="0.6"/>
          <circle cx="74" cy="152" r="1.5" fill="#333" opacity="0.5"/>
          <circle cx="86" cy="155" r="2" fill="#333" opacity="0.45"/>
          <!-- No HEPA label -->
          <rect x="93" y="155" width="29" height="12" rx="3" fill="#c0392b" opacity="0.8"/>
          <text x="107" y="164" text-anchor="middle" font-size="5" fill="#fff" font-family="sans-serif" font-weight="700">NO VAC</text>
          <!-- Labels -->
          <text x="80" y="185" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#333" font-family="sans-serif">Brush misses the edges</text>
          <text x="80" y="195" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#333" font-family="sans-serif">creosote stays on walls</text>
          <text x="80" y="210" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#c0392b" font-family="sans-serif" font-weight="700">Soot falls into room</text>
        </svg>
        <ul class="sweep-points sweep-points--manual">
          <li><strong>Brush smaller than the flue</strong> — edges and corners missed</li>
          <li><strong>Won't shift hardened creosote</strong> — the most flammable buildup</li>
          <li><strong>No containment</strong> — soot and debris falls into your home</li>
          <li><strong>Quicker job</strong>, but less of the flue is actually cleaned</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sweep-verdict">
      <strong>The bottom line:</strong> Power sweeping removes more buildup in a single visit, which means a safer chimney and better draw. It's standard practice in the UK and increasingly expected in Australia.
    </div>
  </section>


